comments.text: I didn't realize until I started printing it that this item is a solid infill, not hollow with variable infill able to be selected in simple programs like Cura. I thought it was odd that the estimated time was showing as 5 hours, but chocked it up to the large and abnormally shaped surface area and my default initial layer speed always set very slow (so I can watch the adhesion more accurately). But after it finished 4 layers and was still printing totally solid, I realized what was happening and stopped it after about 8 layers, as I don't have an abundant supply of filament at the moment.

comments.text: I don't use Cura but it sounds like you need to look at your installation and/or settings. The model is manifold and watertight with no internal structure so you shouldn't have any issues in choosing your own infill density. I printed mine either at 20% or 25% infill with a honeycomb pattern with 3 shells and 3 layers top and bottom. Hope that helps.

title: Recessed Fan Control Switchplate with CTC Drill Template

description.text:
This is a recessed switch panel I designed for my CTC printer, although it could be used on just about anything.   
The switches protrude slightly and are easy to operate while being protected from damage.  
The panel is the same size as the LCD screen on the CTC printer, so it looks nice.  :)  I've included the Solidworks part file so that you can rename the switches to whatever you like.  
I printed it in translucent blue PLA and put an LED strip behind it.  I was having problems keeping it from warping, so the "antiwarp" version has grooves in the bottom to help with this.

The drill template is lined up with the bottom edge of the printer and clamped in place.  Drill 4 holes as instructed and use a jig saw or dremel to finish the cut.  The switch panel snaps into snugly into place via the tabs on the back.

comments.text:
I really like this concept however have printed two off I found the warping caused me to be unhappy with the finished item. I copied what I think is a fantastic idea of yours.
I slotted the front insert section printed it face down on glass then stuck the back on after I did my in black with discreet type on the back panel. I also just put masking tape on the front and cut the hole out while still on the print using a craft knife cover up the fans etc with plastic and masking tape to prevent dust getting into the wrong places. I also only put two switches and a knob in the front. I used my back plate for a cutting template. And used sketchup to redo the design. The back panel I printed face up like a box lid with type above and below the switches. Be carful using using snap off blades once you make a knife slot just keep lightly going deeper even all round the cutout. You should get a clean cut out. Don't put you fingers under side while cutting but use a support bit of wood.

description.text: This is a comb I designed for my wife when hers broke. Printed in her favorite color. Now wife approves purchase of 3D Printer :)

Designed in SketchUp. The source files are attached. Note that I had to work in meters as if they were milimeters due to SketchUp's limitation with small objects. I scaled everything down with Netfabb, so the STLs are ready to print. Instructions:
1.- Print comb
2.- Print 8x flowers
3.- Print 8x flower buds Assemble by attaching the buds to the flowers and then to the holes in the comb. It should be a tight fit if your printer is properly calibrated. If you are using ABS plastic you can use a brush to spread some acetone on the buds and flowers so they completely stick. For finishing, I recommend an acetone vapor bath. I did not do it and will do it whenever I have a chance. I printed mine with a Solidoodle 3. Since the comb is large, I had to rotate it slightly to have it fit diagonally.

title: Gimbal Mount plate for DJI Inspire 1

description.text: There's lots of reasons to mount an extra camera on your Inspire 1: two-person FPV, flying a thermal or multispectral camera, etc. This is a mount plate for the Feiyu G3 aircraft gimbal that slots right into my mount system so that the whole system requires no modification to your aircraft (Dual Lock version coming). Simply print and screw gimbal onto plate using included screws. The mating is very solid, so you'll want to pre-thread the holes using one of the screws. It's designed to be paired with the Inspire 1 Video Transmitter Backpack, although that's optional as long as you power the gimbal some other way. If you don't have access to a 3D printer, Shapeways can print it for you.

comments.text: How and where do you connected the gimbal power supply to the main battery or the Inspire itself?
comments.author: SteffGo

comments.text: After trying many different ways, the one that's stuck is drilling through the main battery terminals then soldering in to those holes. From there you'll need to cut down the voltage, but you're right that the hard part is getting any power reliably.
comments.author: SteffGo

comments.text: Thanks for the information! Do you maybe have a picture/photo where you can see the location for the drilling and soldering? Do not want to "search" for it by drilling a bunch of holes ;)
comments.author: eliotg

comments.text: Just wanted to give you props on your complete system, this allows for great additions!!
comments.author: PlaneMd

comments.text: Thanks! I've liked it for that, too!
comments.author: PlaneMd

comments.text: Great design! Are you using a UBEC to power the gimbal or separate battery? Does that gimbal have a built in IMU? Is it possible to have it configured to always point straight down? Thanks :)
comments.author: CaptainSalty

comments.text: Switching regulator (I like Traco's 3.3 and 5V series).  Yes, it knows where gravity is.  It's not configurable per say.  I've created a FLIR mount for instance that points the camera down 45 degrees, but you are limited to what the gimbal can do within its CG and motor limits.  The proper way to tilt at any angle would be to send the PWM signal on its control line.
comments.author: CaptainSalty

English:
The GadgetGrip is an electronic tablet accessory. Its function is to hold or grip a tablet in the most comfortable way possible compared to conventional  electronic tablets covers or protection.
With GadgetGrip, you can use your tablet in any position, whether it’s standing, seated or laying down without putting strain on your posture.
Furthermore, you can remove the handle in order to pack it away in a backpack or handbag without having to remove its whole structure.
 
The design of the GadgetGrip is based on the idea of the already comercialised product “TakeTab”, which is a handle with a sucker sticking itself on the back of your electronic tablet.
After some time (several months), the sucker looses its elasticity and tends to unstick itself.
The GadgetGrip aims to have the same function as TakeTab, with the added advantage/benefit of not losing grip.
The red claws holding the tablet are designed for the iPad air 2 . if you own another type of electronic tablet, you just need to print the corresponding holders and fix them to the universal black base, fitting any brand of electronic tablet of a similar size.
As this is the type of electronic tablet I own, I can only share this one kind of grip for now.
 
Español:
GadgetGrip es un accesorio para tablets. Su función es la de sujetar o agarrar nuestra tablet de una forma más cómoda de lo que ofrecen las fundas convencionales. Con GadgetGrip podrás usar tu tablet en cualquier posición, sea de pie, sentado o estirado sin posturas forzadas. Además podrás quitar el vástago para poder guardar tu tablet en una cartera o mochila sin tener que retirar toda la estructura. GadgetGrip está basado en un producto comercial llamado TakeTab. TakeTab es un vástago que incorpora una ventosa que se pega al tablet por la parte posterior. Con el paso del tiempo la ventosa ha perdido elasticidad y se despega con mucha frecuencia. GadgetGrip tiene el mismo objetivo, pero con la ventaja de que no se despega. Las pinzas de color rojo que abrazan el tablet están diseñadas para el iPad air 2. Si dispones de un tablet diferente solo tienes que imprimir la pinza necesaria para él y encajarla en la base de color negro que es universal para cualquier tablet de dimensiones parecidas. Find the layer on which the temperature should change and insert the "M104 Sxxx" command where "xxx"=the desired temperature

You will need 1x 5mm LED (in white, blue or UV), some wire, 2x small cell batteries, and an empty drinks can (or similar). I've got some smaller LEDs coming in the mail, and I intend to get this small enough to attach to one of my infamous hair clips. The photograph shows my iterations, but it looks a bit like the TARDIS is moving through time in a way that only Baker-era special effects could claim ;)

There are three parts to this construction - the main body, the slide-in back, and the little top for the LED.

  • Print one of each part - I recommend raftless for the main body, and the back, but a raft for the top piece.

  • Take your knife and trim the bottom of the main part - particularly the channels that the back will slide into. Printing raftless, while giving you a nice smooth back, will tend to spread and clog the bottom of those channels.

  • Also trim the back piece, where the raftless oozing will interfere with the sliding action. Do not progress until you have the sliding action for the back, reasonably smooth.

  • Acquire wire. Strip some insulated if you need to. Don't use paperclips - their resistance is surprisingly high.

  • Take two pieces of wire, each approx as long as your hand, and coil it into a flat spring to fit into the battery indentations. Leave a tail that can fit up the sides of the TARDIS body, and closer to the LED position at the top. This will take a bit of fiddling.

  • Insert your LED. I used a 5mm UV LED which seemed to work well. A blue or white 5mm LED would be good too. Diffused would be best, but you can sand down or otherwise diffuse your own. Insert the LED with one leg to the left and one to the right. Using small pliers, bend the legs out to the side so as to touch the ends of the battery coil tails.

  • Solder! Carefully (because soldering close to meltable plastic is FUN!) solder the legs of the LED to the tails of the battery coil tails. This is fiddly.

  • Pop some batteries in, and ensure that the back still slides on nicely. Otherwise, flatten the coils.

  • On the channel on the inside of the TARDIS back panel, trim some conductive material to fit. I used a strip of a drinks can, sanded to ensure good conductive contact. (Drinks cans are coated on the inside and will NOT conduct without sanding!) Glue this strip in to the channel.

  • Slide the back on to the TARDIS body, and check to see if the LED lights with the two battery cells in. If not, swap the batteries around and test again.

  • Dremel down the top of the LED (or leave it as is, if you prefer) and then glue the TARDIS top cap on to the LED.

  • Make the sound - the one where he's left the hand-break on, and grin like a maniac.
    • A Warning - my TARDIS is, like the real one, incredibly temperamental - I'm going to try to improve the battery connections and work out an improved assembly procedure.

Enjoy this anemometer featured with a little bicycle.
Each part has been designed by me, it moves with few wind, I know it's useless but it's nice to watch it moving
Central shaft is in carbon fiber to avoid any issue with PLA material.
you need a ball bearing to let the anemometer move around and another one for central blade.
Gears designed with Blender, all remaining parts using Autodesk Fusion 360
watch video here: https://youtu.be/IMhXD53sVK4
Enjoy

Before you start it is advisable to polish all holes and gears(most important) depending on the quality of your 3D printing. You can start assembling 01-Blade_base and 02-Blade (3 pieces).
Put a ball bearing in the back hole and then attach (with some glue) 03-Blade_base gear as shown in the image
You need a 16cm shaft with 4mm diameter, up to you the material (I used a carbon fiber one). As locking device for the blade I inserted clothespin used for RC cars :)
Then insert 09-support and then 10-upper_pivot in the center of the shaft.
You can now insert 12-rudder. Put some glue to avoid any movement.
Under 10-upper_pivot you need a ball bearing, then insert from the bottom 11-bottom_pivot which needs to be inserted in a separated pole of 16cm height or more Now you can separately assembly the bicycle.
take 04-Chassis_bicyclette, polish all holes, and insert in the front hole 08-Front_gear, at the opposite side insert 05-Wheel. As linchpin I used a toothpick. Do the same operation on the rear using 06-rear_gear and 05-wheel. Now insert in the central hole 07-Central_gear with 13-Pedal. Bicycle is now completed Verify that gears move freely without any interruption or force.
Insert the completed bicycle in 09-support and as shown in the image (joint should be in the center of the bicycle). Looking from the top, apply a very little angle of counterclockwise inclination.
Place the blade in a way that 08-front_gear is close to 03-Blade_base gear and blade moves fluently.
Once correct movement has been verified put some glue on 09-support. Now enjoy the wind with a moving bicycle going nowhere! :)

title: Lower fixing of InSinkErator Evolution 100 garbage disposal.

description.text:
I would like to show you my project, particularly for people having the same problem. I have a sink, which is hung from the bottom by four small bolts. In fear of breaking off the sink, using 3D printer and a few widely available parts, I decided to construct a lower support of the disposal (disposal is still hung from the top). You have to accurately adjust the height of a support, using upper bolts, in order to maintain the correct depreciation. There is depreciation made of fi-18 rubber tube (75 mm) and fi-12 (30mm) inserted into the first one in the lower part of a fixing. Additional parts needed:
  • M3 bolts with nuts (24mm or longer, washers optionally) – 24 pieces
  • M12 bolts (length = distance from the lowest edge of a disposal to the surface where the lower part of the fixing will be + 15mm) – 3 pieces
  • M12 nuts – 6 pieces
  • M12 bolt washers – 3 pieces
    • How to do:
    You have to print the following parts:
    3x Part up 1-3.stl
    3x Part down 1-3.stl
    6x Parts connector 1-6.stl
    Refine fi-3 printed holes by drilling them. Put everything together and adjust. You can also put rubber washer under a disposal. I used window gasket to do it.
    Good luck !!!

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: An usefull helper for the first steps using my printrbot and dremel as a mil. I used the manual control buttons in pronterface. The result is good for the first try, but takes a long time. The dremel mount has some troubles with the forces during milling. I did the first round with a clearance of 0.5mm (the result was between ~0.2 and 1mm clearance). After that I removed 0.1mm per round only in order to keep the forces deep. Used tool: 3.2mm high speed cutter

Assembly
  • Print the needed parts
  • Drill and countersink some holes in the base plate (the two holes in the block have a distance of 40mm)
  • Push 12 nuts into the 2 blocks
  • Prepare 6 nuts for the jaws (destroy the thread on one side of the nuts, so that the screw get stuck)
  • Mount the vices as shown in the pictures
    • BOM
  • 2x printed blocks
  • 2x printed jaws
  • 1x base plate (plywood)
  • 4x M3x10mm flat (countersink) head screws
  • 22x M3 nuts
  • 6x M3x60mm screws (or threaded bars with 6 nuts and 6 lock nuts as heads)

title: Tennis String Vibration Dampener with your LOGO!

description.text:
This design is for a tennis string vibration dampener that can be customized with your personal LOGO.  
Customizing it is very simple, just open Customizer and upload your LOGO image!  
It makes for a nice gadget, and actually is a useful addition to your tennis racquet.  
The dampener should be printed in flexible filament (I used NinjaFlex for mine), and the LOGO needs to be a 100x100 pixels black and white PNG picture.  
You can find a couple of suitable images to use as LOGO in the image files of this Thing.  
It is possible to have the LOGO printed on just the top face or on both faces of the dampener. Printing on both faces requires a better calibrated printer, as support needs to be printed very close to the LOGO for the print to succeed.  
The files section contains examples of printable dampeners, both with LOGO on one face and on both faces.

IMPORTANT: Printing NinjaFlex or (I presume) other flexible filament is not lilke printing regular PLA or ABS. To make the prints succeed, you will have to slow down the printing process to account for the less amount of plastic that gets extruded. Also, I found it useful to reduce the flow rate of my extruder, and to raise the temperatures a bit.  
The prints shown in these pictures where made on an Arduino Materia 101 with white NinjaFlex, printing at 225°C with 0.2mm layer height, 100% linear infill and a 78% flow rate.  
Support needs to be printed, regardless of the choice to have the LOGO on just one or both faces of the dampener.  
Once printed the dampeners can be colored using permanent markers.
